description:
Ctrl+C during \`yarn dev\` frequently leaves the Node server process bound to :3001, causing \`EADDRINUSE\` on the next \`yarn dev\`. Workaround today is \`yarn kill-dev\` or \`lsof -ti :3001 | xargs kill -9\`.

Root cause: \`src/server/server.ts\` calls \`app.listen(PORT)\` but has no SIGINT/SIGTERM handler, so the HTTP server is never explicitly closed on shutdown. \`src/server/db/index.ts\` already has the equivalent handler for the DB pool — the HTTP server just lacks one. Compounded by \`ts-node-dev\`'s known signal-propagation bugs.

## Fix

Add a shutdown handler in \`src/server/server.ts\` that closes the HTTP server on signal, mirroring the pattern in \`db/index.ts\`:

\`\`\`ts
const server = app.listen(PORT, (): void => { /* … */ });

const shutdown = (signal: string) => {
  console.log(\`\n\${signal} received — closing HTTP server\`);
  server.close(() => process.exit(0));
  setTimeout(() => process.exit(1), 5000).unref();
};

process.on("SIGINT", () => shutdown("SIGINT"));
process.on("SIGTERM", () => shutdown("SIGTERM"));
\`\`\`

## Out of scope (separate issue if pursued)

Migrating \`ts-node-dev\` → \`tsx watch\` would also resolve the signal-propagation flakiness and is faster. Worth a follow-up but not required for this fix.

## Verification

1. \`yarn dev\`, then Ctrl+C — server should log the shutdown line and exit cleanly.
2. Immediately re-run \`yarn dev\` — no \`EADDRINUSE\` on :3001.
